[1]
Date: 8 Dec 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez, M.D. <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: AFP via Yahoo News, 8 Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20051208/hl_afp/healthfluukraine_051208170941>

Preliminary results indicate the presence of the lethal H5N1 bird flu virus
in poultry that died en masse in Ukraine's Crimea peninsula last week.
"According to preliminary results it looks to be it," a spokeswoman at the
agriculture ministry told AFP when asked if the H5N1 virus had been detected.
The H5N1 strain has killed nearly 70 people in Asia over the past 2 years.
Earlier, Ukraine's former chief veterinary inspector, Pyotr Verbitsky, was
quoted as saying that preliminary results from a Russian lab showed the
presence of H5N1 strain. "But the tests continue and tomorrow it will be
known for certain," Interfax quoted Verbitsky as saying.
President Viktor Yushchenko fired Verbitsky earlier this week for what he
said was unpreparedness by veterinary authorities for a bird flu outbreak
in Ukraine.
Last Saturday, tests confirmed the presence of an H5-type virus in the
poultry that began dying en masse in the northeast corner of the peninsula
last week. Samples had been forwarded to laboratories in Britain, Italy and
Russia to establish if the virus is of the deadly H5N1 strain, with results
expected this week.
The poultry is thought to have contracted the virus from wild birds,
millions of which use the nearby Sivash saltwater lake as either a
wintering site or a stopover point on their winter migration route.
Yushchenko declared a state of emergency in the affected areas of Ukraine's
southern peninsula in the Black Sea and the villages where the H5 virus has
been confirmed have been placed under quarantine.
