[2]
Date: 9 Dec 2005
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters, 8 Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L08368910.htm>

Tests have confirmed that birds which died in Ukraine last weekend had the
form of avian flu which can be dangerous to humans, officials said on Thursday.
The outbreak was detected in villages on the Crimean peninsula where about
2500 birds died suddenly. Ukraine has been battling to contain its first
outbreak of bird flu and declared a state of emergency in affected areas.
"We have information that the strain H5N1 was detected," Vyacheslav German,
deputy director of the state institute for biotechnology, told a news
conference.
Bird tissue was sent for laboratory tests to an institute in Russia
immediately after officials detected the disease in several villages in the
northeast of the Crimea. Officials said the strain matched the one recently
found in neighbouring Romania and in Russia. They said the bird tissue was
also sent to Britain for further tests. The test results from Russia are
preliminary, but confirmation was expected on Friday.
Local residents said signs of the illness were detected in September 2005
but that no action had been taken.
The Agriculture Ministry said on Thursday that suspected bird flu had been
found in 2 more villages in the same area. Poultry in the area will be
culled, the ministry said.
President Viktor Yushchenko, who toured the affected area on Monday, has
announced a state of emergency, a measure that the Emergency Ministry said
was key to stop the spread of the disease to other parts of the country. He
also ordered the dismissal of chief veterinarian Petro Verbitsky, saying
animal health authorities had failed to act quickly to detect the outbreak.
The Emergency Ministry, which is overseeing measures to contain the
outbreak, is carrying out a cull of domestic poultry in the affected areas
on the Crimean peninsula in the Black Sea -- a major stopping point for
migratory birds heading south for the winter.
So far its staff have seized more than 29 000 birds in house-to-house
checks in villages sealed off by an exclusion zone. The government is
paying for killed birds from $3 for a chicken to $18 for a turkey.
Ukraine is also vaccinating the population in the affected area against
seasonal flu to boost their immunity. The ex-Soviet state has not reported
any cases of bird flu so far in humans.
[Byline: Olena Horodetska]
